        "k_stdev": 2.0
      },
      "hypothesis": "In quiet-bear tape, short-horizon 2-sigma price excursions from the 21-day mean are liquidity-driven overshoots that get absorbed rather than extended, so fading them (both sides) earns above-median per-trade payoffs. The edge is conditional on macro stress staying contained: a flat/inverted curve with stable credit spreads marks a slow-repricing environment where dealers still provide mean-reverting liquidity, and the meta-learner should admit fades when cs_spread_21 and vix_chg_5 show no acceleration.",
      "causal_story": "BEAR_QUIET's thin return tails (median_q 0.519, tight IQR) plus above-median per-trade returns across all primaries indicate an Ornstein-Uhlenbeck-like tape: drift is weakly negative but excursions revert within days, consistent with a persistently flat/inverted curve (us_5y2y_z252 med_q 0.28) suppressing directional risk appetite while liquidity provision remains intact. Fading 2-sigma bands on a 21-bar window (orthogonal to the 20/63-bar regime windows) harvests that reversion; cs_spread_21 and vix_chg_5 let the meta veto fades when absorption is breaking down. filter_events is chosen: 21.4% of bars across 18 dispersed episodes preserves effective-N, unlike stress regimes.",
      "feature_overrides": {
        "add": [
          "us_5y2y_z252",
          "cs_spread_21",
          "vix_chg_5",
          "real_yield_5y_z252d",
          "volume"
        ],
        "drop": []
      },
